{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Jk6UjfJPfFHX179uhzexAU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The openssl-toolbox pod doesn't exist yet. I need to create it. Let me check if there are any existing resources or configurations that might tell me what to use.\n\nLet me plan the approach to enable TLS for CockroachDB:\n\n1. Generate certificates using an openssl-toolbox pod (I need to create it)\n2. Create Kubernetes secrets with the certificates\n3. Update the StatefulSet to use TLS mode instead of `--insecure`\n\nHere's what needs to be done:\n\n1. Create a CA key and certificate\n2. Create a node certificate (signed by CA) for each node\n3. Generate a client certificate for the root user\n4. Store these as Kubernetes secrets\n5. Update the StatefulSet to mount the secrets and use `--certs-dir` instead of `--insecure`\n\nCockroachDB expects the certificates to be organized in a specific directory structure with the CA certificate, node certificate and key, and root client certificate all in the `/cockroach/cockroach-certs/` directory.\n\nFor the node certificate's Subject Alternative Names, I need to include localhost, the pod DNS names like `crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`, the service names, and the namespace. I could use CockroachDB's built-in `cockroach cert` command or openssl directly. The cleanest approach is to create a Kubernetes job with openssl to generate all the certificates at once, then store them as secrets and mount them in the StatefulSet.\n\nActually, `cockroach cert` is the preferred method here. I'm using it to generate the CA certificate, then the node certificates with all the necessary SANs, and finally the client certificates.\n\nI can run these commands directly on an existing CockroachDB pod and copy the generated certificates back locally, which avoids needing a separate openssl container. My plan is to execute the cert generation on crdb-cluster-0, create Kubernetes secrets from the resulting certificates, and then update the StatefulSet to use them in secure mode.\n\nGenerating the CA and node certificates with all necessary SANs...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the secrets structure—I need to create two separate secrets: one for node-to-node and node-to-client TLS communication containing the CA certificate and node credentials, and another for client authentication with the root user's certificate and key.\n\nMy plan is to generate all the certificates on the first pod, extract them, create the appropriate Kubernetes secrets, then update the StatefulSet to mount the node secret at the proper directory and remove the insecure flag while adding the certs directory path. Since the SQL test command also needs access to the client root certificate, I'll need to ensure both the node and client root certificates are available in the mounted directory.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing there's a permissions issue to work through—CockroachDB requires specific file permissions for the certificates (0644 for public certs, 0600 for keys), but Kubernetes secrets mounted as volumes default to 0644 for all files. I need to figure out how CockroachDB handles this when the key files don't have the expected restrictive permissions.\n\nI could use `defaultMode: 0600` in the volume mount or run a chmod command in an init container to fix permissions after mounting. Let me try the secret approach first and see if it works, then move forward with generating the certificates on the first pod and creating the Kubernetes secret from them.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":564,"cache_read_input_tokens":31444,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":564},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":